1 3. Maintain a minimum grade point of average of 2.0 on a 4.0
2 scale;
3 4. Maintain satisfactory participation in the Oklahoma National
4 Guard; and
5 5. Possess a Military Occupational Specialty (MOS) or Air Force
6 Specialty Code (AFSC) after his or her first semester.
7 G. An eligible Guard member seeking assistance pursuant to the
8 provisions of this section shall submit an application on a form
9 prescribed by the Military Department of the State of Oklahoma to
10 the Educational Service Office of the Military Department prior to
11 the semester for which assistance is sought. The eligible Guard
12 member’s Commander or his or her designee shall confirm a member’s
13 standing and eligibility to the technology center school in which
14 the student is enrolled. The Military Department may establish a
15 cap on the number of eligible Guard members allowed to participate
16 per semester per technology center school program.
17 H. The eligible Guard member’s Commander may deny an
18 application submitted by an eligible Guard member for continued
19 program assistance if he or she fails to comply with the provisions
20 of paragraph 1, 2, 3, 4, or 5 of subsection F of this section.
21 I. An eligible Guard member seeking assistance pursuant to this
22 section who is eligible for federal education benefits for
23 vocational training shall exhaust all such federal benefits, when
24 available, first.
